</li>
<li>
<p>Jisc reports on <a href="https://www.jisc.ac.uk/news/uk-education-divided-in-its-adoption-of-the-cloud-14-jul-2015">the use of public and private cloud with UK HE</a> and FE.&nbsp; [JISC]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Surrey is offering a 15pt Masters module: <a href="http://www.surrey.ac.uk/tel/profdev/designingtel/">Designing Technology Enhanced Learning: A Learning Design Studio Approach</a>.&nbsp; [Matthew Moran]</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Ernst and Young <a href="https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/ernst-and-young-drops-degree-classification-threshold-graduate-recruitment">no longer requires new hires to have a degree</a> as it has found &lsquo;no evidence&rsquo; of a link to achievement in professional assessments.&nbsp; [Beccy Dresden]</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</p>
<p><strong>And Finally&hellip;</strong></p>
<p><em>[Stephen Downes]</em></p>
<p>We would probably all agree that rich use of language leads to better society and learning, but Stephen Downes writes &ndash; &ldquo;We certainly need language of some sort in order to create models and representations. &nbsp;But to my mind, that's not how we learn. &nbsp;Consider <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AVaITA7eBZE">this case from the BBC demonstrating a crow undertaking a complex eight-stage task</a>. &nbsp;Crows caw, but they don't have a language. &nbsp;This is the sort of behaviour that any learning theory needs to explain. &nbsp;It's not enough to theorize how <em>humans</em> learn. &nbsp;We need to know how <em>learning happens</em>, no matter where it occurs.&rdquo;</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Thu, 17 Sep 2015 16:08:59 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
