<p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~</p>
<p><strong>And Finally&hellip;</strong></p>
<p><em>[Open Culture; Google; TechCrunch]</em></p>
<p>Google continues to expand its panoramic offerings.&nbsp; In addition to the <a href="http://www.googleartproject.com/">virtual art gallery</a> and Street View explorations of <a href="http://google-latlong.blogspot.co.uk/2013/09/explore-galapagos-and-be-darwin-for-day.html">the Galapagos Islands</a> and the <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2015/03/12/google-partners-with-local-nonprofit-to-bring-street-view-better-maps-to-mount-everest-region">Mount Everest region</a> (all reported in earlier digests), you can now take look around (and below the surface of) <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2015/04/20/google-brings-street-view-to-loch-ness">Loch Ness</a>.&nbsp; There&rsquo;s also an interactive tour of the <a href="http://g.co/insideabbeyroad">Abbey Road Studios</a> that lets you explore the recording studio, watch interviews and mini documentaries, and view iconic photos.&nbsp;</p>
<p>But if all that realism is a bit much, Swedish coder Einar &Ouml;berg has created <a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/cool-tech/brick-street-view-turns-google-maps-into-lego/">Brick Street View</a> which allows you to tour around any part of the world as if it was constructed in Lego, complete with toy cars and trees.</p>]]></description>
