<li>Jo DiDonato lists his <a href="http://blogs.2elearning.com/2012/07/top-25-free-e-learning-authoring-tools/">top 25 free e-learning authoring tools</a>.&nbsp; [Elearning!]</li>
<li>Acer is donating hundreds of <a href="http://www.tomshardware.com/news/Acer-Olympics-Laptops-e-learning-foundation-london-schools,16768.html">ex-Olympic laptops</a> to London primary schools.&nbsp; [JE]</li>
<li>The <a href="http://techcrunch.com/2012/08/01/getting-married-wedding-party-collects-photos-from-guests-phones-to-create-beautiful-online-albums">Wedding Party app</a> allows guests to create a digital wedding album by sharing photos, videos and notes.&nbsp; [TechCrunch] </li>
<li>Brien Posey suggests <a href="http://www.techrepublic.com/blog/five-apps/five-youtube-video-downloaders-worth-a-look/1480">five YouTube video downloaders</a> that allow users to watch clips offline.&nbsp; [Stephen Downes]</li>
<li>Seven UK HEIs are forming <a href="http://www.create.ac.uk/">CREATe</a> &ndash; a Centre for Creativity, Regulation, Enterprise and Technology.&nbsp; [Matthew Moran]</li>
<li>Mohamed Kharbach&rsquo;s Ed Tech blog lists 7 free <a href="http://www.educatorstechnology.com/2012/08/free-learning-and-teaching-resources.html">learning and teaching resources about Mars</a> and the Curiosity rover.&nbsp; [Ed Tech and Mobile Learning]</li>
<li>Nabil Zary curates a useful Scoop.it site devoted to <a href="http://www.scoop.it/t/e-learning-in-medical-education">eLearning in medical education</a>.&nbsp; [Matthew Moran]</li>
</ul>
<p>~~~~~~~~</p>
<p><strong>And Finally&hellip;</strong></p>
<p><em>[UserFocus; BBC; ReadWriteWeb; Mashable]</em></p>
<p>Can you cope with any more Olympics material?&nbsp;</p>
<p>On the <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/bbcinternet/2012/07/olympics_design.html">BBC internet blog site</a>, Nick Haley gives a fascinating insight into how the Beeb&rsquo;s desktop, tablet, mobile and connected TV sites were designed in terms of their features, layout, usability and testing.&nbsp; The Corporation reports 2m downloads of its Olympic app and 55m worldwide online visits to its sports coverage during the games (and video is apparently remaining live on its <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/2012/">Olympic site</a> until January); however, according to <a href="http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/olympics-online-who-won-the-gold-medal-for-best-website.php">ReadWriteWeb&rsquo;s assessment of Olympic sites</a>, it only gets a bronze, having been pipped at the post by the New York Times and the Guardian.&nbsp; There are also several good interactive examples on the <a href="http://elearningexamples.com/?s=olympic">ElearningExamples site</a>, including an excellent unpicking of a <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2012/07/19/sports/olympics/the-toughest-vault.html">gymnastic vault</a> (NY Times), an analysis of <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/olympic_infographics_and_data/9397299/Olympics-2012-Team-GB-athletes-diets-interactive.html">an Olympian&rsquo;s diet</a> (Telegraph) and an HTML5 <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/interactive/2012/jul/23/could-you-be-a-medallist">&lsquo;could you be a medallist?&rsquo;</a> game (Guardian).</p>
<p>Mashable reports that the games generated around <a href="http://mashable.com/2012/08/13/olympics-generated-150-million-tweets/">150 million tweets</a>, including one which reunited a man with his <a href="http://mashable.com/2012/08/15/twitter-olympic-ticket/">lost Olympic ticket</a>, and an infographic from EDF Energy tracked <a href="http://mashable.com/2012/08/13/uk-twitter-olympics/">the UK&rsquo;s twitter mood</a> during each day of the games.</p>
